    cellular: "The abdomen is divided into nine regions or four quadrants for clinical reference. Key structures visible on abdominal radiographs include the liver (right upper quadrant), spleen (left upper quadrant), kidneys (retroperitoneal, flanking the spine), psoas muscles (retroperitoneal), and bowel gas patterns. The abdominal aorta courses along the left side of the vertebral column. Calcifications may be seen in kidneys, gallbladder, pancreas, aorta, and lymph nodes. The four abdominal quadrants are RUQ, LUQ, RLQ, and LLQ, divided by the umbilical vertical and horizontal lines.",
